06753nam a22006975i 9780228002826DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280028267 a10.1515/97802280028262doi  a(DE-B1597)657082  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aB995.T3 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a19122300aInterpreting Modernity :bEssays on the Work of Charles Taylor /ced. by Jacob Levy, Daniel M. Weinstock, Jocelyn Maclure. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tCharles Taylor: A Biographical Sketch -- tEpistemology, Philosophy of Mind, and Philosophy of Language -- tTo Follow a Rule -- tCharles Taylor's Conception of Language: And the Current Debates about a Theory of Meaning -- tTaylor's Engaged Pluralism -- tReligion and Modernity -- tState-Religion Connections and Multicultural Citizenship -- tTaylor, Rawls, and Secularism -- tMoral Agency and the Self I -- tWhat If Anything Is Wrong with Positive Liberty? : The Struggles of Agency In a Non-Ideal World -- tWhat's Right with Positive Liberty: Agency, Autonomy, and The Other -- tThe Interpretation of Modernity -- tWhatever Happened to the Ontic Logos? :German Idealism and the Legitimacy of Modernity -- tTaylor, Fullness, and Vitality -- tMoral Agency and the Self II -- tSelf-Creation or Self-Discovery? -- tAn Explicitative Conception of Moral Theory -- tCharles Taylor and Ethical Naturalism -- tPolitical Philosophy, Recognition, and Multiculturalism -- tProtecting Freedom of Religion in the Secular Age -- tTwo Conceptions of Indian Secularism -- tMemory, Multiculturalism, and the Sources of Democratic Solidarity -- tCanadian Politics -- tRecognition in Its Place -- tA Conversation between Charles Taylor, Jacob T. Levy, Daniel M. Weinstock, and Jocelyn Maclure -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere are few philosophical questions to which Charles Taylor has not devoted his attention. His work has made powerful contributions to our understanding of action, language, and mind. He has had a lasting impact on our understanding of the way in which the social sciences should be practised, taking an interpretive stance in opposition to dominant positivist methodologies. Taylor's powerful critiques of atomistic versions of liberalism have redefined the agenda of political philosophers. He has produced prodigious intellectual histories aiming to excavate the origins of the way in which we have construed the modern self, and of the complex intellectual and spiritual trajectories that have culminated in modern secularism. Despite the apparent diversity of Taylor's work, it is driven by a unified vision. Throughout his writings, Taylor opposes reductive conceptions of the human and of human societies that empiricist and positivist thinkers from David Hume to B.F. Skinner believed would lend rigour to the human sciences. In their place, Taylor has articulated a vision of humans as interpretive beings who can be understood neither individually nor collectively without reference to the fundamental goods and values through which they make sense of their lives. The contributors to this volume, all distinguished philosophers and social theorists in their own right, offer critical assessments of Taylor's writings. Taken together, they provide the reader with an unrivalled perspective on the full extent of Charles Taylor's contribution to modern philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aAnthony Appiah, Kw